{ [White: Jeremy Silman] [Black: F.R (1539)][Los Angeles, 2004]
This is a pretty clearly advantageous position for white. Silman notes an important detail that white can eventually get his knight to f5 by playing Ng3 but black can never exploit the hole on f4 because his knight can't use g6 or e6. Also, white's bishop on a4 threatens to trade off the key bishop on d7. While this looks quite hopeless, if I were playing black I'd try something super aggressive like a timely f5 pawn sac. It might make a losing position worse but it would atleast leave black with some counterplay. }
1. Rb3 { Very creative move. I wouldn't have seen this (blocking up the a4 bishop looks like an anti pattern but there's no good way to attack it. White threatens to double up on the b file and open it up. } { Creative idea. Definitely feels strange to block the bishops retreat. } 1... Bxa4 (1... cxb4 2. axb4 Rc8 3. c5 bxc5 4. bxc5 $18 dxc5? 5. d6 c4 6. dxc7 cxd3 7. cxb8=Q { Whites a piece ahead. }) 2. Nxa4 Nd7 { Black happy to at least trade a piece and complete development. } 3. Rab1 Rab8 4. R1b2 Rfe8 (4... Rfc8 5. Qb1 cxb4 6. Rxb4 a5 7. Bxb6 Nxb6 8. Rxb6 Rxb6 9. Nxb6 $18)  (4... b5? 5. bxc5! bxa4 6. Rxb8 Nxb8 7. cxd6 Qxd6 8. c5 Qd7 9. Qb1 Qd8 10. Rb7 $18) 5. Qb1 { This setup is called 'Alekhine's Gun'. All heavy artillery is pointing down the b file with the bxc5 break coming soon. } 5... Bf8 6. bxc5 bxc5 7. Rb7 Rxb7 8. Rxb7 Qa5 9. Qc2 Nb8? (9... Qd8 10. Bd2 $18) 10. Rb6 Nd7 11. Bd2 { 1-0. } *


