aps gets in trouble here concretely because of allowing Ng4. The space advantage plays a part. The point is that black has to tread a fine line here. } 26... Ng7 { White has a positional advantage here. Not only does he have a lot more space in the centre and on the right flank, his pawns have successfully prevented black knights from penetrating throughout the game. Question is, how can white convert this advantage before giving his opponent time to recover? In this game, white is never really able to. } (26... Nf6! { [%cal Gb7d8,Gf6e8] }) 27. Ng4 f6 28. Nh4 Bd4 29. Rbc1 { Honestly not sure opposing c-file is best or not. } 29... Nd8 30. Rxc7 Rxc7 31. Rc1 { Rc1 almost seems counter intuitive to me. White has more space and there no entry points on the c-file. Not clear is benefits white unless he can trade all rooks and penetrate the c-line with the queen. } 31... Rxc1 32. Bxc1 Qe7 33. Qc2 Ne8 34. Nh6+ Kg7 35. a4 { My impression of this game is that Galkin is a favorite and the young Romanov is afraid to take even a tiny risk. Maybe ba was necessary to avoid getting rolled off the board. } 35... Nf7 (35... bxa4 36. Bxa6 { Im not convinced white is even better here. }) 36. Nxf7 Kxf7 37. Nf3 Bb6 (37... bxa4 38. Bxa6 Ba7) 38. a5 { Now a6 is a weakness. } 38... Ba7 39. Ne1 Qd8 40. Ng2 Qc8 41. Qxc8 Bxc8 42. Be3 Bxe3 43. Nxe3 Ng7 44. Nd1 f5 45. Nc3 Bd7 46. Kg2 fxe4 47. Nxe4 Ke7 48. g4 Ne8 49. Kg3 1/2-1/2


